'''Christian Arno''' (born 1 December 1978) is the founder and Managing Director of UK translation company [[Lingo24]].

Arno established Lingo24 as a 22-year-old [[Oxford University]] graduate in 2001. He won the Shell LiveWIRE ‘Young Entrepreneur of the Year’ award in 2003.<ref>[http://www.shell-livewire.org/business-library/case-studies/lingo24 Shell LiveWIRE, Christian Arno, Lingo24] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090714171955/http://www.shell-livewire.org/business-library/case-studies/lingo24 |date=14 July 2009 }}</ref> As of 2009, he is a finalist in the ‘Entrepreneur of the Year’ category at the 2009 National Business Awards for [[Scotland]].<ref>[http://edinburghnews.scotsman.com/scotland/City-translators-spoken-highly-of.5229746.jp Edinburgh Evening News, City Translators Spoken Highly of in Prize Shortlist, 2 May 2009]</ref>

Arno has also become a business commentator, and has been enlisted by Brand Republic to give advice for businesses seeking to globalise,<ref>[http://mediazone.brighttalk.com/comm/Haymarket/d1dd4377ce-12987-2822-13302 Brand Republic, Tapping into Emerging Markets through Effective Communications, April 2009]</ref> while the Sunday Times,<ref>[http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/entrepreneur/article6299766.ece Sunday Times, How I Made it: Christian Arno, founder of Lingo24.com, 17 May 2009]</ref> Telegraph,<ref>[http://www.lingo24.com/resources/pdf/The_Telegraph_19th_May_2009.pdf The Telegraph, Speaking in mother tongues translates into a success story, 19 May 2009] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090611165125/http://www.lingo24.com/resources/pdf/The_Telegraph_19th_May_2009.pdf |date=11 June 2009 }}</ref> and Financial Times<ref>[http://www.lingo24.com/resources/pdf/Financial_Times_18th_April_2009.pdf Financial Times, Messages of doom don't mean the end of the world, 18 April 2009]</ref> have also used Arno and Lingo24 as a case study in a range of business features.

Arno has also contracted to work for Smarta, an online support platform for business owners and entrepreneurs backed by [[Deborah Meaden]] from [[Dragons' Den]], to provide expert advice to entrepreneurs looking to grow their businesses,<ref>[http://www.smarta.com/inspiration/comment/christian-arno Smarta, Who is Christian?] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090614180700/http://www.smarta.com/inspiration/comment/christian-arno |date=14 June 2009 }}</ref> and he was also part of a panel of experts for the Guardian newspaper's Live Q&A session: what can I do with a degree in languages?, in July 2010.<ref>[http://careers.guardian.co.uk/careers-blog/live-q-a-what-can-i-do-with-a-degree-in-languages The Guardian, Live Q&A session: what can I do with a degree in languages? 21 July 2010]</ref>

Later in 2010, Arno was commissioned to provide regular columns for a number of online publications, such as Econsultancy,<ref>[http://econsultancy.com/uk/blog/authors/christian-arno-2 Econsultancy]</ref> Search Engine Journal,<ref>[http://www.searchenginejournal.com/author/christian-arno/ Search Engine Journal]</ref> Search Engine Watch
<ref>[http://searchenginewatch.com/3640500/all_articles Search Engine Watch]</ref> and Brand Republic.<ref>[http://community.brandrepublic.com/members/2788795.aspx Brand Republic]</ref> Arno became a Fellow of the [[British-American Project]] at its 2013 conference at the [[University of Cambridge]].

